window.SDM_BANKS["c03"] = {"course_id":"c03","course_title":"Value Crafted: The Value Proposition Canvas","version":"2.0-pilot","items":[{"id":"c03_b01","bloom":"remember","lo":null,"competency":"Recall customer-profile elements","stem":"Which lists the three elements of the <em>customer profile</em> side of the Value Proposition Canvas?","options":{"A":"Features, benefits, pricing","B":"Jobs, pains, gains","C":"Acquisition, retention, revenue","D":"Strengths, weaknesses, opportunities"},"key":"B","explanation":"The circle holds jobs, pains, and gains: what the customer is trying to do, what bites along the way, and what they hope to enable.","explanations":{"A":"Features, benefits, and pricing all live on the company's side of the table. The customer profile describes the customer's life, not your offer.","B":"Jobs, pains, gains. The circle describes the customer before your product enters the room.","C":"Acquisition, retention, and revenue belong to business-model metrics, a later conversation entirely.","D":"That is SWOT vocabulary, a strategy tool for analyzing a company, not a customer."}},{"id":"c03_b02","bloom":"remember","lo":null,"competency":"Recall value-map elements","stem":"Which lists the three elements of the <em>value map</em> side of the Value Proposition Canvas?","options":{"A":"Pricing, packaging, positioning","B":"Customers, channels, revenue","C":"Jobs, pains, gains","D":"Products &amp; services, pain relievers, gain creators"},"key":"D","explanation":"The square holds products and services, pain relievers, and gain creators: what you ship and the specific ways it removes pains and produces gains.","explanations":{"A":"The three Ps are marketing vocabulary. The value map is about what the offer does for the customer, not how it is sold.","B":"Customers, channels, and revenue live on the Business Model Canvas, the bigger tool this one plugs into.","C":"Jobs, pains, and gains are the other side: the customer profile circle.","D":"Products and services, pain relievers, gain creators. The square describes your offer in terms of the circle."}},{"id":"c03_b03","bloom":"understand","lo":"lo1","competency":"Explain why VPC sits between validation and business model","stem":"Why does the Value Proposition Canvas sit between problem validation and business-model design?","options":{"A":"Because the canvas forces the founder to map proposed value 1:1 against ranked customer pains and gains before committing to a solution.","B":"Because business models cannot be designed without first knowing the customer's address.","C":"Because the canvas is required by most accelerators.","D":"Because the canvas replaces customer interviews."},"key":"A","explanation":"The canvas is the translation step: it forces the proposed value to map 1:1 onto ranked pains and gains before any building or business-model work.","explanations":{"A":"Exactly. Validation tells you the problem is real; the canvas makes sure the solution you are about to design points at what the customer ranks first.","B":"Location has nothing to do with it. The canvas cares about jobs, pains, and gains, not addresses.","C":"Some accelerators do ask for it, but that is a symptom of its usefulness, not the reason it exists.","D":"The canvas runs on interview material. Without Course 2 evidence, the boxes fill up with guesses."}},{"id":"c03_b04","bloom":"understand","lo":"lo1","competency":"Explain the purpose of 1:1 mapping","stem":"Why does the canvas require pain relievers and gain creators to be mapped 1:1 to ranked customer pains and gains?","options":{"A":"To make the canvas visually balanced.","B":"To meet investor reporting requirements.","C":"To prevent the founder from building feature soup that addresses low-priority customer concerns.","D":"To simplify pricing."},"key":"C","explanation":"The 1:1 rule is a feature-soup prevention tool: every item on the value side must point at something the customer actually ranked.","explanations":{"A":"Visual balance is a side effect. The rule is about discipline, not aesthetics.","B":"Investors never audit your canvas. The 1:1 rule protects your build order, not your pitch deck.","C":"Correct. Without the rule, founders pile up relievers for interesting-but-unranked concerns and call the pile a product.","D":"Pricing is a later decision, and the canvas does not touch it."}},{"id":"c03_b05","bloom":"understand","lo":null,"competency":"Classify a pain","stem":"A customer says: <em>\"I dread doing the laundry on Sundays because it eats four hours of my only day off.\"</em> How is this best categorized on the customer profile?","options":{"A":"A gain, a positive outcome the customer wants.","B":"A pain, an active source of frustration the customer wants to escape.","C":"A job, a task the customer hires a product to do.","D":"A product feature."},"key":"B","explanation":"Dread plus lost hours is an active frustration attached to a job: a pain.","explanations":{"A":"There is no positive outcome named here, only something to escape. Gains reach toward a new good thing.","B":"The word \"dread\" is the tell: an active frustration the customer wants gone while doing the laundry job.","C":"The job underneath is keeping the household clothed. The dread and the lost four hours are the pain riding on that job.","D":"Features live on the value map. Nothing here describes a product."}},{"id":"c03_b06","bloom":"understand","lo":null,"competency":"Classify a gain","stem":"A customer says: <em>\"I'd love to spend Saturday mornings with my kids.\"</em> How is this best categorized?","options":{"A":"A pain.","B":"A product feature.","C":"A pain reliever.","D":"A gain, a positive outcome the customer wants to enable."},"key":"D","explanation":"Nothing hurts in this sentence. The customer is reaching for a new positive outcome: a gain.","explanations":{"A":"No frustration is named. \"I'd love to\" reaches forward; pains push away.","B":"Features belong to the offer. This is a statement about the customer's life.","C":"Pain relievers live on the value map, and there is no pain here to relieve.","D":"A gain: a positive outcome the customer wants to enable, in their own words."}},{"id":"c03_b07","bloom":"apply","lo":"lo2","competency":"Apply the ranking method","stem":"A founder has listed six customer pains and has resources to relieve only three. Which ranking method matches the discipline taught in this course?","options":{"A":"Pick the three pains her team is most enthusiastic about.","B":"Score each pain by frequency × severity × addressability, then keep the three with the highest scores.","C":"Pick the three pains mentioned most by her social media followers.","D":"Pick the three pains her largest competitor is also addressing."},"key":"B","explanation":"Frequency times severity times addressability, then sort and keep the top three. The math protects the ranking from the founder's enthusiasm.","explanations":{"A":"Team enthusiasm is exactly what the scoring exists to protect you from. Exciting pains are not always ranked pains.","B":"Score, sort, keep three. Frequency counts how often it bites, severity how hard, addressability whether you can credibly fix it.","C":"Followers who comment are not the customers who pay, and loudness is not severity.","D":"Copying a competitor's map means inheriting their customer, who may rank pains differently from yours."}},{"id":"c03_b08","bloom":"apply","lo":"lo2","competency":"Apply the wording test","stem":"A founder writes: <em>\"Our enterprise-grade AI-powered platform leverages advanced algorithms to optimize your workflow.\"</em> Applying the wording test, what is the MAIN problem?","options":{"A":"It is too long.","B":"It does not include a price.","C":"It is written entirely in the founder's vocabulary; none of the words came from customer interviews.","D":"It does not mention competitors."},"key":"C","explanation":"Every noun came from a pitch deck. The wording test counts whose words the proposition uses, and here the customer's count is zero.","explanations":{"A":"Length is not the flaw. A longer sentence in the customer's words would still land.","B":"Propositions rarely carry the price. That is a different test.","C":"Platform, leverage, optimize: founder vocabulary from end to end. The customer cannot recognize their own life in it, so it cannot convert.","D":"Competitor mentions belong in positioning documents, not in the proposition."}},{"id":"c03_b09","bloom":"apply","lo":"lo2","competency":"Apply 1:1 reliever design","stem":"A team has three top-ranked customer pains and is about to design pain relievers. Which approach matches the 1:1 discipline?","options":{"A":"Design one pain reliever per ranked pain, three relievers mapped 1:1, and resist the urge to add a fourth.","B":"Design seven pain relievers covering the full pain list to be safe.","C":"Combine all three pains into one universal pain reliever.","D":"Skip pain relievers and focus on gain creators instead."},"key":"A","explanation":"Three pains, three relievers, three lines, and the discipline to stop there.","explanations":{"A":"One reliever per ranked pain, nothing floating. The restraint is the discipline.","B":"Seven relievers is feature soup with a safety excuse. The unranked four dilute the product nobody asked for.","C":"One universal reliever usually means a vague reliever. Distinct pains deserve distinct, nameable relief.","D":"Gains matter too, but skipping the ranked pains abandons the customer's loudest reasons to switch."}},{"id":"c03_b10","bloom":"apply","lo":"lo2","competency":"Apply customer-language extraction","stem":"A founder has six interview transcripts and wants phrases for her value proposition wording. Which method matches the wording test?","options":{"A":"Use the language of her favorite business textbook.","B":"Use synonyms of customer words that sound more professional.","C":"Use her co-founder's preferred industry vocabulary.","D":"Use the exact phrases customers used when they described the pain or gain, even if grammatically rough."},"key":"D","explanation":"Exact phrases, rough edges and all. Polish is not what converts; recognition is.","explanations":{"A":"Textbook language is nobody's spoken language. The customer cannot recognize themselves in it.","B":"Professional synonyms are a downgrade: each substitution moves the sentence further from the customer's mouth.","C":"Industry vocabulary impresses peers and loses customers. The proposition is for the customer.","D":"The exact words, even ungrammatical ones. \"Sayang ang gabi ko\" converts better than \"suboptimal evening utilization\" ever will."}},{"id":"c03_b11","bloom":"analyze","lo":"lo3","competency":"Diagnose a misaligned reliever","stem":"A canvas shows three customer pains: (1) long checkout time, (2) unclear return policy, (3) hidden shipping costs. The value side lists three pain relievers: (a) one-click checkout, (b) free unlimited returns, (c) AI-powered product recommendations. Which pain reliever is MISALIGNED?","options":{"A":"One-click checkout","B":"Free unlimited returns","C":"AI-powered product recommendations","D":"The three pain relievers are all aligned."},"key":"C","explanation":"Recommendations point at no listed pain. Checkout maps to pain 1 and returns maps to pain 2, but pain 3 (hidden shipping costs) is left unserved.","explanations":{"A":"One-click checkout points straight at the long checkout time. Aligned.","B":"Free returns answer the unclear return policy. Aligned.","C":"Recommendations answer nothing on the pain list, while hidden shipping costs go unrelieved. A floating feature and an abandoned pain at the same time.","D":"Count the lines: two connect, one floats, one pain has no reliever. That is not alignment."}},{"id":"c03_b12","bloom":"analyze","lo":"lo3","competency":"Diagnose creator overload","stem":"A founder's canvas lists five gain creators and only two top-ranked customer gains. Applying the alignment discipline, what is the MAIN issue?","options":{"A":"Three gain creators are unmapped; they likely serve gains the customer did not rank, which is how feature soup starts.","B":"The canvas needs more pain relievers.","C":"The customer-profile side is too short and needs more research.","D":"The value map is correctly sized; five gain creators is the standard."},"key":"A","explanation":"Five creators minus two ranked gains leaves three items pointing at nothing the customer asked for.","explanations":{"A":"Three creators float. Each one costs build time and product clarity while serving a gain nobody ranked.","B":"Nothing in the mismatch says pains are underserved. The problem is on the gain side.","C":"Possible, but the observed issue is the surplus on the value side, not a shortage of research.","D":"There is no standard count. The right number of creators is the number of top-ranked gains."}},{"id":"c03_b13","bloom":"analyze","lo":"lo3","competency":"Distinguish creator from reliever by job","stem":"A customer outcome reads: <em>\"Saves two hours of grocery time per week.\"</em> Under what condition is this best classified as a GAIN CREATOR rather than a pain reliever?","options":{"A":"When the customer is willing to pay for it.","B":"When the customer is a parent.","C":"When the savings exceed three hours.","D":"When the customer's job is to enable a different positive outcome, like spending time with family, not to escape an active frustration."},"key":"D","explanation":"The job decides the side of the canvas. Escaping a chore is pain relief; enabling Saturday with the kids is gain creation.","explanations":{"A":"Willingness to pay applies to both sides. It does not tell you which side you are on.","B":"Demographics do not classify outcomes. Two parents can hire the same product for different jobs.","C":"The size of the saving changes the score, not the classification.","D":"The customer's job is the deciding test. Same two hours: escape a burden and it is relief; enable a wanted morning and it is a gain."}},{"id":"c03_b14","bloom":"evaluate","lo":"lo4","competency":"Evaluate proposition fit","stem":"Four value propositions for the same meal-planning app for working parents. Which BEST shows fit between ranked customer pains and gains and the value map?","options":{"A":"\"Our app uses AI to plan meals.\"","B":"\"Spend Saturday morning with your kids, not stuck in the grocery aisle. We plan and order the week's meals while you sleep.\"","C":"\"The most advanced meal-planning algorithm in the Philippines.\"","D":"\"An award-winning, multi-functional meal management platform for the modern household.\""},"key":"B","explanation":"It names the ranked gain (Saturday with the kids), the ranked pain (the grocery aisle), and the reliever that connects them, all in words a parent would say.","explanations":{"A":"A feature statement. It says what the technology does and nothing about what the parent gets.","B":"The gain, the pain, and the mechanism, in the customer's own vocabulary. You can hear a parent forwarding this to a friend.","C":"Superlatives about the algorithm serve the founder's pride, not the parent's Saturday.","D":"Award-winning, multi-functional, platform: three phrases no parent has ever said about dinner."}},{"id":"c03_b15","bloom":"evaluate","lo":"lo4","competency":"Evaluate wording quality","stem":"A founder reads two propositions aloud. (i) <em>\"Our enterprise solution leverages best-in-class technology to optimize logistics workflows.\"</em> (ii) <em>\"Stop spending Friday night reconciling supplier receipts. We close your books before you close the shop.\"</em> Both target SMEs that struggle with manual reconciliation. Which assessment is MOST defensible?","options":{"A":"Both are equally good; they describe the same product.","B":"(i) is stronger; it signals enterprise credibility.","C":"(ii) is stronger; it is written in the customer's vocabulary and names the specific pain moment and the wanted outcome.","D":"Neither is strong; both need pricing information."},"key":"C","explanation":"(ii) names the hated moment and the wanted moment in the customer's own words. (i) is founder vocabulary from end to end.","explanations":{"A":"Same product, very different sentences. The wording test measures recognition, and only one of these is recognizable.","B":"Enterprise credibility signals impress procurement committees, not the SME owner drowning in Friday receipts.","C":"Friday night, receipts, close the shop: the customer's own moments and words. Structural fit plus recognizable wording.","D":"Propositions do not carry prices. Adding a peso figure to (i) would not make anyone recognize their life in it."}}]};
